Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| Location | Pattern | Issue |
|----------|---------|-------|
| `RunLoop` `while(true)` | Cancellable work loop | Needs `CancellationToken` |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call interruption | Must wake on cancellation |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) | Replace with token signaling |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` | Replace with cooperative cancel |

## Bug in Original Code

There's a race condition: multiple `Enqueue` calls can fire `Set()` but `Reset()` is called after only one `Dequeue`, losing signals. The migrated version fixes this.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // WaitAny wakes on either a new event OR cancellation
            WaitHandle.WaitAny([_newEvent.WaitHandle, token.WaitHandle]);

            if (token.IsCancellationRequested)
                break;

            // Drain all queued items (fixes original race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0)
                        break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }

            _newEvent.Reset();
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();           // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);     // wait for graceful exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation is sufficient
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Key Changes

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Cooperative exit |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `WaitHandle.WaitAny([event, token])` | Wakes on cancel *or* new work |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Token's WaitHandle unblocks WaitAny |
| `Thread.Abort()` | Removed | Not supported; loop exits cooperatively |
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter weight; preferred in .NET 8 |
| Single dequeue per signal | Drain loop | Fixes lost-signal race condition |
| No cleanup | `IDisposable` | Disposes `CancellationTokenSource` and event |

## Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` has no equivalent** — if `Handle(item)` hangs forever, `Stop()` will block at `Join`. Add a `CancellationToken` to `Handle` so it can cooperate too.
2. **Don't forget to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — it leaks timer/callback resources.
3. **`Reset()` must come *after* draining** — resetting before dequeue (as the original did) drops signals when multiple items arrive between iterations.
4. **`Thread.Interrupt` is also obsolete** (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9) — don't use it as a stepping-stone replacement.
